post_text:
Superintendent Cordes will be interviewed by KFGO at Vision Ford on Thursday at 8:00 a.m. She will be talking about the school's Angel Funds.

Breckenridge Schools lunch policy is that all students will be fed a healthy hot meal regardless of the family's lunch account balance. Knowing there are times when a family might go through a difficult financial time and need temporary help, a generous community member donated to the district asking that it be used to help cover unpaid lunch balances. This was the beginning of a fund known as Angel Funds. In addition to helping families with the hot lunch program, these funds are also used to ensure younger students receive a healthy snack during the school day regardless of their lunch account balance. Through generous staff and community donations, the fund has grown and provided support for many struggling families.

To donate online: https://www.schoolpay.com/parent/mip/Mdes

You may also mail a check to:

Breckenridge Public School, 810 Beede Avenue, Breckenridge, MN 56520

Due to retirements, our Food Service Department has 1.5 openings. The positions will be approximately 4 hours or 5 hours in length. One position is daily, M-F, and the other position, is 2-3 days per week, shared. Pay is per MSEA contract found on the school website. Please apply online at www,breckenridge.k12.mn.us & go to employment opportunities under quick links. Call the district office with questions at 643-6822 or email Food Services Director Steph Beyer at beyers@breckenridge.k12.mn.us

We also have openings for substitutes in the Food Service Department. Training is offered and pay is $10.75 per hour.

shared_text:
Breckenridge Youth Program
July 28 at 12:49 PM ¬∑

2020 COWBOY WRESTLING CAMP
Register today at www.breckenridge.k12.mn.us
Under Quicklinks choose Webstore-Community Education

Due to guidelines in place as a result of Covid-19, we will be holding our wrestling camp outdoors this year. We will be working on technique & agility, playing a lot of games and having treats/awards for the wrestlers after each session. We will not be using a mat so wrestling shoes and headgear are not needed. Some items to be aware of:

¬∑ Coaches and wrestlers will be screened and their temperatures checked prior to participation.

¬∑ We will be using the field west of the swimming pool for our camp. If the weather doesn‚Äôt cooperate on a particular day, we will cancel the session.

¬∑ We are limiting our sessions to one hour (10:30 ‚Äì 11:30). Original schedule was 10:30 -12:00

¬∑ Bring a water bottle clearly marked with your name. Take care of bathroom breaks before you arrive.

Breckenridge music teachers Mrs. Bouressa (choir) and Mr. Niska (elementary music) were pleased to participate in a virtual choir this summer. You can also see Mr. Lippert (choir 2017-18) at 2:12. Excellence in music performance is a lifelong joy. Enjoy the video!

post_text: UPDATE on summer youth programs:
shared_text:
Breckenridge Youth Program
May 26 at 2:20 PM ¬∑

ATTENTION:
Due to COVID-19, we have been in a holding pattern regarding Breckenridge Youth Summer Programs. We are asking for your continued patience as we continue to navigate through the unknown. Our hope is that we will still try to proceed with as many of our summer programs as possible and adjust as needed going forward. Many classes have been cancelled and others adjusted to later dates. We hope to get news tomorrow that will give us more direction.

If you have already registered for Babe Ruth Baseball or Twin Town Baseball and seasons do get cancelled you will receive a FULL refund.

Brochures will be emailed out as soon as we can after the green light is given and online registration will open. Thank you for your understanding during these uncertain times!

ü¶Üü¶ÜGet Duckedü¶Üü¶Ü

Breckenridge DECA would like to give back to our community. We understand the hardships everyone is going through during this time. So we are doing a fundraiser to raise money for local businesses in the form of gift cards, which will be given away to the community.

How the fundraiser will work: You can spread positivity and laughs by "ducking" your friends and family's yards. When you duck someone's yard it will be filled with rubber ducks and left up for 3 days unless they want to pay to get it removed earlier.

The money that is raised will go directly to local businesses in the form of gift cards that will then be given away to the community in the near future.

ü¶ÜMore info will be released soon.

ü¶ÜIf interested pm us!

Friday, May 1st, is School Lunch Hero Day. Some heroes wear Aprons, not Capes! Thanks ladies for all you do!

We would like to recognize the School Nutrition Staff during this time of preparing and serving sack breakfast and lunches. They have been working hard packing meals for the children of Breckenridge! On Wednesday, March 18, sack meals were prepared for 39 students. On Monday, April 27, meals were prepared for 325 students!

HS: Deb Jordheim, Judy Smith, April Lauritsen, Joan Vagts, Diane Christensen

Elem: Nancy Heitkamp, Lori Formaneck, Sandy Blaise, Pam Braun

April 30, 2020 - Community Update from Superintendent Cordes:

At the special school board meeting on Thursday, April 30th, the following changes were approved to the 2019-20 school calendar.
‚Ä¢ The last student contact day has been moved to Friday, May 22nd.
‚Ä¢ The last day of distance learning delivery will be Wednesday, May 20th.
‚Ä¢ May 21 and May 22 will be used as catch up days with students as well as scheduling collection times for student‚Äôs books, materials and technology devices.
‚Ä¢ May 26 will be a wrap-up day for teachers.
‚Ä¢ May 27, 28, and 29 will be teacher professional development.
‚Ä¢ Meal and childcare delivery will continue through May 28th.
‚Ä¢ Graduation is still planned for Sunday, May 31st.
Note that on May 1st and 4th there will be no distance learning. Meal delivery and childcare will continue on those days.
Please call 643-6822 or email questions@isd846.org with any questions

post_text: Distance Learning has been a learning curve for College Speech class where students need to navigate their own recordings during a Google Meet session. Isabel Friederichs was kind enough to add "comic relief" for the class on her April 4 speaking day. First, two computer cameras failed Isabel (one recording the floor, one recording her in "night vision"); then, her cell phone gave her further difficulty. But, like a true Cowgirl, Izzy persevered, going on to "wow" her classmate with a wonderful extemporaneous speech about why Amazon should pay taxes. Way to show your "true grit," Isabel!

Ms. Kelly and Ms. Rikki
April 22 at 10:40 AM ¬∑

Hello!!! Man do we miss doing our Mindful Mornings with you all!! Let Ms. Kelly take you on a little journey to the beach today!

Get outside in this warmer weather and practice mindfulness using your 5 senses!
5- things you see
4- things you hear
3- things you can touch
2- things you can smell
1- thing you can taste

Give it a try, it is all about practice!
We miss you!

#bettertogether

It's NOT too late! You may still sign up for meals for your child(ren)!

Fill out the form and let us know which location you will be picking up the meals for your child(ren)!

Meals are offered daily from 9:00 - 9:30a.m. and you may pick them up in town at the following Breckenridge locations.
Breckenridge Senior Center
St Mary's School
Valley Christian Church
Breckenridge Elementary, Door 9 (northeast corner of building)
Outlying areas are sent out twice weekly, on Mondays and Thursdays (Campbell, Foxhome, Kent and Wolverton).

After you sign up, your meals will be ready the next day at the pickup spot that you designated on the survey form! All meals are FREE!

If you have any questions please contact Steph Beyer at 218-641-4028 or by email at beyers@isd846.org

post_text: Update regarding Summer Youth Programs
shared_text:
Breckenridge Youth Program
April 8 at 10:11 AM ¬∑

ATTENTION:
Due to COVID-19, we are in a holding pattern regarding Breckenridge Youth Summer Programs. We are asking for your patience as we navigate through the unknown. Once we are given the green light and no longer need to shelter at home; we will try to proceed with as many of our summer programs and adjust as needed.
If you have already registered for Babe Ruth Baseball or Twin Town Baseball and seasons do get cancelled you will receive a FULL refund. Other than those registered already; we will hold off, until further notice, on all other registrations.

Brochures will be emailed out as soon as we can after the green light is given. Thank you for your understanding during these uncertain times!

Day 2 of SCDC was filled with competitions and a lot of team building! DECA Members had a full day with their competitive events and Marketing Cluster Exams but also had some time to enjoy together as a group. Unfortunately, no one qualified for the finals round but this was a great experience for our 3-time State qualifying seniors and for our sophomore and freshman future leaders. Day 3 will consist of closing events and a lot of naps on the drive back to Breckenridge! Awesome job to all the DECA State Qualifiers! And a huge thank you to our wonderful chaperone, Sheri Friederichs!

Breckenridge DECA
March 2 at 12:05 AM ¬∑

As Day 1 of the 2020 DECA State Leadership Conference wraps up, Breckenridge Chapter, Students, and Advisor were recognized with a few awards! The Chapter won a Chapter Achievement Award for the Membership Campaign by increasing our membership by over 100% from last year! Claire Aigner and Isabel Friederichs were recognized as Outstanding Members for the Chapter, and Advisor Mr. Grahn was recognized as an Outstanding Advisor through a nomination by members.

In addition to the awards, DECA Members began their initial competitions by competing in Marketing Plan events and Exams for the chance to move on to the Finals round. Day 2 kicks off at 8 AM tomorrow as Members will continue with a day of competition before the Preliminary Awards Ceremony tomorrow evening!

post_text: The Breck Speech Team competed at a large meet in Morris on Saturday, February 22. Out of 20 schools, they placed 9th with Jolena Munro placing 3rd in the category of Great Speeches, Aja Tabb placing 4th in Dramatic Interpretation, and Vanessa Sunderland and Owen Skovholt placing 5th and 7th in Extemporaneous Speaking. The team is looking forward to another meet in Battle Lake this Saturday. Go Cowboys and Cowgirls!
